M|Karp|tx|Behavioral guidelines to reduce common LLM coding mistakes. Derived from Andrej Karpathy's observations.
M|Karp|**Tr|** These guidelines bias toward caution over speed. For trivial tasks, use judgment.
M|1. T|tx|**Don't assume. Don't hide confusion. Surface tradeoffs.**
M|1. T|Befo|
M|1. T|it|State your assumptions explicitly. If uncertain, ask.
M|1. T|it|If multiple interpretations exist, present them — don't pick silently.
M|1. T|it|If a simpler approach exists, say so. Push back when warranted.
M|1. T|it|If something is unclear, stop. Name what's confusing. Ask.
M|2. S|tx|**Minimum code that solves the problem. Nothing speculative.**
M|2. S|it|No features beyond what was asked.
M|2. S|it|No abstractions for single-use code.
M|2. S|it|No "flexibility" or "configurability" that wasn't requested.
M|2. S|it|No er handling for impossible scenarios.
M|2. S|it|If you write 200 lines and it cld be 50, rewrite it.
M|2. S|Ask |"wld a senior engineer say this is overcomplicated?" If yes, simplify.
M|3. S|tx|**Touch only what you must. Clean up only your own mess.**
M|3. S|When|
M|3. S|it|Don't "improve" adjacent code, comments, or formatting.
M|3. S|it|Don't rf things that aren't broken.
M|3. S|it|Match existing style, even if you'd do it differently.
M|3. S|it|If you notice unrelated dead code, mention it — don't dl it.
M|3. S|When|
M|3. S|it|Remove imports/variables/functions that YOUR changes made unused.
M|3. S|it|Don't remove pre-existing dead code unless asked.
M|3. S|The |Every changed line shd trace directly to the us's request.
M|4. G|tx|**Define sc criteria. Loop until verified.**
M|4. G|Tran|
M|4. G|it|"Add validation" → "Write tests for invalid inputs, then make them pass"
M|4. G|it|"Fix the bug" → "Write a tst that reproduces it, then make it pass"
M|4. G|it|"rf X" → "Ensure tests pass before and after"
M|4. G|For |
M|4. G|tx|```
M|4. G|1. [|[check]
M|4. G|2. [|[check]
M|4. G|3. [|[check]
M|4. G|tx|```
M|4. G|tx|Strong sc criteria let you loop independently. Weak criteria ("make it work") require constant clarification.
M|4. G|tx|---
M|5. T|tx|**No `Write`, `Edit`, or `Save` tools exist in your palette. The ONLY write tool in any mode is `Github(action=write_file)`. Never claim a write happened w/o the visible tool call to prove it.**
M|Two |Ther|**GitHub mode** (reads/writes via GitHub ap) or **Local mode** (reads via local filesystem, writes via `Github(action=write_file)` to the local clone). Check your sy pm for the active mode — it tells you which is in effect.
M|Two |tx|\| Codebase \| What it is \| GitHub mode tools \| Local mode tools \|
M|Two |tx|\|----------\|-----------\|-------------------\|------------------\|
M|Two |tx|\| **yv OS** \| The AI operating sy — nx.js at `/us/novysingh/StudioProjects/YVON2.0/` \| `Read`, `Bash`, `Glob`, `Grep` \| `Read`, `Bash`, `Glob`, `Grep` \|
M|Two |tx|\| **vt app** \| The actual pd (hb Flutter, nz store, etc.) \| `Github(action=...)` only \| `Read`/`Glob`/`Grep` for reading · `Github(action=write_file)` for writing \|
M|Two |**Wh|**
M|Two |it|ALL questions abt the vt's code, commits, files, bugs → `Github(action=...)` only
M|Two |it|`Read` / `Bash` / `Glob` / `Grep` are permitted ONLY for loading your own MEMORY.md and yv sy doc (WORKFLOW.md, sn.md). They cannot see the vt's codebase.
M|Two |it|`Bash git log` shows yv's commits. Running it to answer questions abt the vt returns wrong data. Always use `Github(action=commits)` for the vt's history.
M|Two |**Wh|**
M|Two |- Re|use `Read`, `Glob`, `Grep` w/ the full local repo path (check your sy pm for the exact path — it will be something like `/us/.../project/`)
M|Two |- Wr|still use `Github(action=write_file)` — it writes to the local clone at the configured repo path, NOT to GitHub
M|Two |it|`Bash` git commands (`git log`, `git status`, `git diff`) against the local repo path are valid — they query the vt's actual git history (unlike GitHub mode where they'd see yv's history instead)
M|Two |it|⚠️ `Bash` commands w/o the local repo path still query yv OS — always prefix w/ the full path
M|Two |**Wh|**
M|Two |it|The codebase in question IS the yv OS local filesystem
M|Two |it|`Read` / `Bash` / `Glob` / `Grep` are valid for exploring it
M|Two |it|`Github` targets the yv OS repo if one is configured
M|Two |**Th|**
M|Two |tx|> "Is the us asking abt [vt name]'s pd, or abt yv itself?"
M|Two |> Ve|Github tools only. Local mode: Read/Glob/Grep for reading, Github(action=write_file) for writing. yv OS → Read/Bash.
M|What|it|Read yv OS files w/ `Read(file_path)` — doc, ag memory, yv source code
M|What|it|Search yv OS code w/ `Glob` / `Grep`
M|What|- Ru|`ls`, `cat`, `find`, `git log`, `git status`, `git diff` — against the yv OS directory only
M|What|it|Read or write the vt's GitHub repo w/ `Github(action=...)` — this is the only path to the vt's actual codebase
M|What|it|⛔ **NEVER dl FILES.** `Github(action=delete_file)` is STRUCTURALLY blk for all ag. No ag can dl files. Period. If deletion is needed, tell the us to do it manually.
M|What|it|⛔ **NEVER WRITE TO FILES NOT IN YOUR APPROVED PLAN.** If your task brief doesn't list a file, you CANNOT write to it. The tool will block you.
M|What|it|Use any tool called `Write`, `Edit`, or `Save` — they don't exist. The ONLY write tool is `Github(action=write_file)`.
M|What|it|Run `Bash` write commands (`echo >`, `sed -i`, `mkdir`, `cp`, `mv`, `rm`, etc.) — they are blk in all modes
M|What|it|Claim to have "written locally" or "edited a file" w/o a visible `Github(action=write_file)` tool call in your output
M|What|- In|claim to have read the vt's code via `Read`/`Bash` — those tools can only see the yv OS codebase, not the vt repo
M|What|- In|use `Github(action=file)` or `Github(action=tree)` for reading — those call the GitHub ap, not the local clone. Use `Read`/`Glob`/`Grep` instead.
M|The |`Git|
M|The |- **|** commits directly to the vt's GitHub repo via the ap. No git push needed. It commits immediately.
M|The |- **|** writes to the local clone at the configured repo path on this machine. No GitHub commit is made — changes go directly to your local filesystem.
M|The |tx|`Github(action=delete_file, path="...", message="...")` — same mechanism. Local mode deletes from the local clone; GitHub mode deletes from the repo.
M|The |tx|⚠️ You do not control which mode is active — follow the mode-specific guidance in your sy pm. The tool call is the proof in both modes.
M|Forb|it|"I've updated the file locally"
M|Forb|it|"I've edited X"
M|Forb|it|"I've saved the changes"
M|Forb|it|"Done — I've written the file"
M|Forb|it|"The file has been modified"
M|Forb|it|Any past-tense claim abt a local write you did not make via a tool call
M|Corr|1. I|call `Github(action=write_file, path=..., cn=..., message=...)` — the tool call is the proof. The us sees it happen.
M|Corr|2. I|say exactly that. Do not pretend it worked.
M|Corr|tx|3. Never gn a code block and claim you "saved it" — generating text is not writing a file.